# Backend development logging

Every backend HTTP/GraphQL surface should have **minimal logging in development**:

1. **Request access** — method + route/path when a request is handled
2. **Response status** — at least the status code when the request finishes (duration is fine but optional)
3. **Errors** — `console.error` (or equivalent) when something unexpected fails (thrown errors, handler failures)

Keep it quiet outside development. Do not dump full request bodies or secrets by default.

Reference pattern: `apps/ai-api/src/request_log.ts` (`withDevRequestLogging`).

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — minimal access + finish + unexpected throw
console.log(`[api] request received ${method} ${path}`)
// … handle …
console.log(`[api] request finished ${method} ${path} → ${status}`)
// on unexpected failure:
console.error(`[api] request threw ${method} ${path}`, err)
```

When adding a new API or middleware entrypoint, wire this (or reuse shared kit helpers) rather than shipping silent handlers. Colocate GraphQL/resolver unexpected failures with an error log before rethrowing or mapping to a client error.
